def display_img(img, gray=False):
    '''
    img = input image or image like array
    gray = bool for displaying a grayscale image
    '''
    plt.axis('off')
    if(gray):
        plt.imshow(img, cmap='gray', vmin=0, vmax=255)
        plt.show()
    else:
        plt.imshow(img)
        plt.show()
In [3]:
def plot_histo(img):
    hist, bin_edges = np.histogram(img.flatten(),256,[0,256])
    distrib = hist.cumsum()
    normalized_CDF = distrib * float(hist.max()) / distrib.max()
    plt.plot(normalized_CDF, color = 'r')
    plt.hist(img.flatten(),256,[0,256], color = 'blue')
    plt.xlim([0,256])
    plt.legend(('cdf','histogram'), loc = 'upper left')
    plt.show()

Creating function to contain all steps in process for rapid prototyping¶

In [15]:
def img_correct(img, clip_limit=1, kernal=(3,3)):
    '''   
    Takes:  img - BGR version of your image
            clip_limit - adjustable and defines luminosity corrections, values less than 1 make the image darker
            kernal - must be square and greater than or equal to a (3x3) matrix
    
    Returns:
            None
    '''
    lab_img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2LAB)
    l, a, b = cv2.split(lab_img)

    clahe = cv2.createCLAHE(clipLimit=clip_limit, tileGridSize=kernal)
    clahe_l = clahe.apply(l)
    
    #debug plotting and image comparison
    plot_histo(l)
    plot_histo(clahe_l)
    display_img(cv2.cvtColor(l, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
    display_img(cv2.cvtColor(clahe_l, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))

    #apply fix to lum
    adj_img = cv2.merge((clahe_l,a,b))
    adj_img_rgb = cv2.cvtColor(adj_img, cv2.COLOR_LAB2RGB)
    
    display_img(adj_img_rgb)
